      Oh ElonI am sorry to  keep  talking about  it because it is so stupid=
, but there really is something unprecedented and amazing and almost magica=
l about Elon Musk=E2=80=99s continuing ability and inclination=C2=A0to move=
 the prices of Bitcoin and Dogecoin with his slightest whim. Imagine if you=
 had gone to Warren Buffett 30 years ago =E2=80=94=C2=A0or J.P. Morgan 120 =
years ago =E2=80=94=C2=A0and told him: Here is a lamp. In the lamp is a gen=
ie. When you rub the lamp, the genie will come out and=C2=A0invent two asse=
ts. They will trade like stocks in many ways, but unlike stocks they (1) wi=
ll not be subject to U.S. securities laws, (2) will trade 24 hours a day, s=
even days a week, and (3) will not represent claims on any businesses or ca=
sh flows. One will have a market cap =E2=80=94=C2=A0a total circulating sup=
ply =E2=80=94=C2=A0of about a trillion dollars; the other will be smaller b=
ut still like $65 billion. They will be liquid=C2=A0enough, with lots of pe=
ople trading=C2=A0many billions of dollars=E2=80=99 worth per day;=C2=A0you=
 can buy or sell lots of them without too much price impact. And: Any time =
you want the price of either one to go up or down by 10% or more, you can j=
ust whisper =E2=80=9Cprice go up=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Cprice go down=E2=80=
=9D into the lamp, and it will happen instantly. You are the only person wh=
o can do this, and you can do it as often as you want.How much would Warren=
 Buffett pay for that lamp? I suppose its value is not literally infinite: =
Once you have all the money you could ever spend, you might get bored of wh=
ispering to the lamp all the time=C2=A0and go do something else.[1] But it =
is as close to infinite as you=E2=80=99re likely to get, as close to a free=
-money perpetual motion machine as you=E2=80=99ll ever see=C2=A0in finance.=
 You can quickly, easily, silently buy billions of dollars=E2=80=99 worth o=
f a liquid unregulated financial asset and then=C2=A0tell it to go up, and =
it will go up. Then you can sell it,=C2=A0tell it to go down, and repeat.=
=C2=A0I will say again that I have no particular reason to think that Elon =
Musk is monetizing this magical ability that he has, and in fact I assume h=
e=E2=80=99s not, but:=09He definitely has the power to move Bitcoin and Dog=
ecoin prices whenever he feels like it.=09He definitely exercises that powe=
r with some frequency and with no apparent pattern.=09He definitely has the=
 money to buy lots of Bitcoin and Dogecoin before making them go up.=09If h=
e did do that, he probably would not have much in the way of disclosure obl=
igations, at least not real-time disclosure obligations.[2]=09Similarly he =
could easily sell them before making them go down, without much in the way =
of disclosure obligations.=09The regulation and policing of Bitcoin and Dog=
ecoin trading are rather less comprehensive and aggressive than the regulat=
ion and policing of=C2=A0stock trading.So if he was doing the magic-lamp tr=
ading strategy =E2=80=94=C2=A0which, again, I don=E2=80=99t think he is =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0it would look, to an outside observer,=C2=A0more or less exactl=
y like what he=E2=80=99s currently doing.=C2=A0I just think that if you pre=
sented this possibility to any famous investor throughout history they woul=
d absolutely faint with excitement. And here Musk is, the second-richest pe=
rson in the world, either doing it =E2=80=94=C2=A0in which case it=E2=80=99=
s one of the greatest trades, and also one of the greatest trolls, in histo=
ry =E2=80=94=C2=A0or=C2=A0not doing it, rubbing the lamp and making Bitcoin=
 and Dogecoin go up and down and up and down and up and down with his whims=
,=C2=A0just=C2=A0for fun, leaving billions of dollars of profit on the tabl=
e because he doesn=E2=80=99t need the money and has the purest imaginable c=
ommitment to internet trolling.Anyway:Dogecoin soared on Friday after Elon =
Musk said he was working with the crypto's developers to improve its effici=
ency as a means of payment.The Tesla (TSLA) boss, who has previously said h=
is Dogecoin tweets shouldn't be taken seriously, tweeted that he was "worki=
ng with doge devs to improve system transaction efficiency" and said the wo=
rk was "potentially promising."The cryptocurrency, which was conceived as a=
 joke in 2013, rose over 30% on Friday morning following Musk's tweet. It w=
as trading at $0.53, having reached as high as $0.56.But also:Elon Musk con=
tinued to whipsaw the price of Bitcoin, briefly sending it to the lowest si=
nce February after implying in a Twitter exchange Sunday that Tesla Inc. ma=
y sell or has sold its cryptocurrency holdings.Bitcoin slid below $45,000 f=
or the first time in almost three months after the billionaire owner of the=
 electric-car maker seemed to agree with a Twitter post that said Tesla sho=
uld divest what at one point was a $1.5 billion stake in the largest crypto=
currency. It traded at $45,270 as of 5:51 p.m. in New York, down about $4,0=
00 from where it ended Friday. =E2=80=A6His latest dustup with Bitcoin star=
ted with a tweet from a person using the handle @CryptoWhale, which said, =
=E2=80=9CBitcoiners are going to slap themselves next quarter when they fin=
d out Tesla dumped the rest of their #Bitcoin holdings. With the amount of =
hate @elonmusk is getting, I wouldn=E2=80=99t blame him...=E2=80=9DThe Tesl=
a chief executive officer responded, =E2=80=9CIndeed.=E2=80=9DBut  also, al=
so:Bitcoin steadied after Elon Musk said Tesla Inc. hasn=E2=80=99t sold fro=
m its holdings of the token, clarifying earlier comments that seemed to imp=
ly the electric vehicle maker may sell or has sold its stake.The largest di=
gital currency was at $44,900 as of 7:21 a.m. in London on Monday, after Mu=
sk in a tweet said: =E2=80=9CTo clarify speculation, Tesla has not sold any=
 Bitcoin.=E2=80=9D Earlier, the token slid to $42,185, the lowest since Feb=
ruary. It=E2=80=99s about $20,000 off the record set in April.Tesla definit=
ely=C2=A0has=C2=A0sold some Bitcoin (in March), though, so you have to inte=
rpret that one a bit. Presumably he meant it hasn=E2=80=99t sold between th=
e disclosed sales in March and the time he hit send on that tweet, but I ca=
n=E2=80=99t be sure about that.Here is the Friday Dogecoin tweet, which I g=
uess was a follow-up to his tweet on Wednesday that made Bitcoin  go down b=
y 15%. =E2=80=9CWorking with Doge devs to improve system transaction effici=
ency. Potentially promising.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0Is Musk working with Dogecoin de=
velopers to improve its efficiency? Do you care? =E2=80=9CSystem transactio=
n efficiency=E2=80=9D?=C2=A0Here is a claim that he=E2=80=99s been doing th=
at =E2=80=94=C2=A0with =E2=80=9Cthe team of four part-time Dogecoin develop=
ers=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0since 2019. He tweeted it Friday. The point tha=
t I want to make here is that if he tweets today =E2=80=9Cthese Dogecoin de=
velopers are kind of lame, they don=E2=80=99t laugh at my jokes,=E2=80=9D h=
e will wipe billions of dollars off of Dogecoin=E2=80=99s market cap in 10 =
minutes. And then if he tweets tomorrow =E2=80=9Cbut they=E2=80=99re good d=
evelopers, I like them anyway,=E2=80=9D he will add billions of dollars to =
Dogecoin=E2=80=99s market cap in 10 minutes. And then if he tweets on Wedne=
sday =E2=80=9Cbut I just don=E2=80=99t think our partnership is working out=
,=E2=80=9D it will subtract billions of dollars. And then if he tweets on T=
hursday =E2=80=9Cah we resolved our issues and now Dogecoin=C2=A0will be le=
gal tender on Mars,=E2=80=9D it will add billions of dollars. And I can kee=
p typing these=C2=A0things until you=E2=80=99re bored, but Elon Musk can ke=
ep typing these things=C2=A0and make money come out each time.=C2=A0Here=E2=
=80=99s the Sunday Bitcoin tweet=C2=A0(=E2=80=9CIndeed=E2=80=9D), and here=
=E2=80=99s the overnight clarification. Did Tesla sell its Bitcoins before =
Musk tanked the price on Wednesday? Or after, but before he tanked it again=
 on Sunday? Is Tesla buying more now? Who even knows. The point here is tha=
t (1) it could have, (2) he is messing with us, and (3) whether he is messi=
ng with us by whipsawing=C2=A0the price of Bitcoin=C2=A0and trading it=C2=
=A0or by whipsawing the price of Bitcoin=C2=A0and not trading it=C2=A0doesn=
=E2=80=99t matter that much;=C2=A0either way is bizarre and incredible.In a=
n ideal world =E2=80=94=C2=A0in a good fairy tale =E2=80=94=C2=A0Musk would=
 lose the lamp and it would be found by some impoverished urchin, or by me.=
 This magic power really is wasted on the second-richest person in the worl=
d! Still it is amazing.Yet more of thisMeanwhile here is, allegedly, a bot =
that buys Dogecoin when Musk tweets about it. Nothing in this newsletter is=
 ever=C2=A0investing advice, I own no Dogecoin or Bitcoin, my money is in d=
umb index funds, and yet a part of me thinks it is weird to have any invest=
ing strategy=C2=A0other than =E2=80=9Cbuy Dogecoin or Bitcoin when Elon Mus=
k tweets nice things about them, and sell them when he tweets bad things ab=
out them.=E2=80=9D What=C2=A0is=C2=A0finance, these days, but that? =E2=80=
=9CSurely at some subconscious level people want to order their lives in ac=
cordance with the cryptic instructions of a charismatic flying zillionaire,=
=E2=80=9D I  wrote way back in February, and=C2=A0you could automate that.E=
lsewhere here=E2=80=99s a Dogecoin millionaire:=E2=80=9CDogecoin has the be=
st branding of all cryptocurrency,=E2=80=9D he said. =E2=80=9CIf you put in=
 front of me all the symbols of Ethereum, Bitcoin, Litecoin =E2=80=94 every=
thing just looks super high tech and futuristic. And Dogecoin just looks li=
ke: Hey, guys, what=E2=80=99s up?=E2=80=9DHe imagines that newbies investin=
g in cryptocurrency for the first time might gravitate toward something fun=
 and recognizable, and that Dogecoin might eventually become a kind of on-r=
amp to the larger world of virtual money.=E2=80=9CI feel like eventually we=
=E2=80=99re all going to be buying and selling things with memes, and Dogec=
oin is going to lead the way,=E2=80=9D he said.Strange as his investment th=
esis might seem, it=E2=80=99s hard to argue with the results.It=E2=80=99s n=
ot even strange! The thesis in buying any non-cash-flowing asset =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0Dogecoin, Bitcoin, gold, art, whatever =E2=80=94=C2=A0has to be =E2=
=80=9Cother people will want to buy this thing too,=E2=80=9D and=C2=A0some =
sort of mass-psychology=C2=A0story =E2=80=94=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cother people wil=
l want to buy this thing because it=E2=80=99s fun and approachable=E2=80=9D=
 =E2=80=94 seems like the most reasonable way to support that thesis. We  t=
alked the other day about a company that paid Elon Musk in Dogecoin to laun=
ch a satellite into space, as a way to make the price of Dogecoin go up. I =
said: =E2=80=9CReally if postmodern finance is primarily a matter of mass p=
sychology, isn=E2=80=99t it =E2=80=A6 marketing?=E2=80=9D If you=E2=80=99re=
 going to pick a cryptocurrency to buy, why wouldn=E2=80=99t you pick the o=
ne with the best branding? What else is there?Still elsewhere,=C2=A0here=E2=
=80=99s Ethan Allen:Ethan Allen Interiors,=C2=A0a furniture company that de=
finitely won=E2=80=99t let you pay in bitcoin, has seen a surge of retail-i=
nvestor interest recently. Its ticker symbol, ETH, is the same as the one u=
sed for red-hot ethereum. Message boards for the stock are mostly filled wi=
th banter about the cryptocurrency, not the company.=E2=80=9CWe=E2=80=99ve =
definitely seen a massive increase on a percentage basis in mistaken activi=
ty on the Ethan Allen stream,=E2=80=9D says Rishi Khanna, Chief Executive O=
fficer of social investing site Stocktwits.Yeah okay fine that=E2=80=99s go=
od too. Again, nothing here is ever investing advice, but if you are the ch=
ief financial officer of Ethan Allen Interiors Inc.,=C2=A0how have you not =
pivoted to Ethereum? Ethan Allen has a $750 million market cap; last quarte=
r it had net income of $15.6 million. Here is the trade:=09Buy like $10 mil=
lion worth of Ethereum.=09Put out a press release saying =E2=80=9CEthan All=
en Interiors Inc. (ETH) (ETH!!!) (the ticker is ETH) is moving a portion of=
 its cash balances into Ethereum and exploring ways to become more Ethereum=
-focused, maybe you can pay for a couch with crypto, smart couch contracts,=
 whatever, we=E2=80=99ll figure it out.=E2=80=9D=09The stock quintuples, be=
cause ETH.=09Do a billion-dollar stock offering saying like =E2=80=9CETH is=
 selling stock to invest the proceeds in Ethereum.=E2=80=9D=09The stock dou=
bles during the stock offering.=09Put 90% of the proceeds into Ethereum and=
 pay yourself a giant bonus with the rest.=09=E2=80=9CEthan Allen Interiors=
 has changed its name to Ethereum Interiors; the ticker symbol will not cha=
nge, nor will the couches.=E2=80=9D=09Honestly how have they not done this =
yet, it is the freest of free money.I really am sorry about all this, I am =
keenly aware of how dumb it is, but what an amazing time we live in. If you=
 are designing complex derivatives on decentralized smart-contract platform=
s I am sure you are having a good time but in a very real economic sense yo=
u are doing it wrong; the best trades right now are the absolute stupidest =
ones.


