r: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bor=
der-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #c=
cc;"> I proposed</a> what I called the Boredom Markets Hypothesis. Retail i=
nvestors, the theory goes, trade stocks because it is more fun than whateve=
r else they could be doing with their time. Typically it is fun to trade st=
ocks when stocks are going rapidly up, and not especially fun otherwise, so=
 retail investors have a historical tendency=C2=A0to pile into bubbles near=
 the peak. Typically=C2=A0it is pretty fun to do other things, and there ar=
e new fun things to do every day, so over time it gets harder and harder fo=
r the stock market to compete with other forms of fun. So retail investing =
has, over the years, lost some market share in the things-people-do-for-fun=
 market, and there has been a rise of index funds and robo-advisers and oth=
er ways for people to outsource this no-longer-especially-fun activity.</p>=
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But the Covid-19 pandemic changed those dynami=
cs: Even though (last April, when we started talking about this) stocks wer=
e not doing particularly well, and it was not=C2=A0<em>absolutely=C2=A0</em=
>all that fun to trade them, it was=C2=A0<em>relatively=C2=A0</em>fun to tr=
ade them just because there was nothing else to do. I wrote:</p><blockquote=
><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The weird thing about the coronavirus crisis =
is that it simultaneously (1) caused a stock market crash and (2) eliminate=
d most forms of fun. If you like eating at restaurants or bowling or going =
to movies or going out dancing, now you can=E2=80=99t. If you like watching=
 sports, there are no sports. If you like casinos, they are closed. You=E2=
=80=99re pretty much stuck inside with your phone. You can trade stocks for=
 free on your phone. That might be fun? It isn=E2=80=99t that fun, compared=
 to either (1) what you=E2=80=99d normally do for fun or (2) trading stocks=
 not in the middle of a recessionary crisis, but those are not the availabl=
e competition.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And then, you k=
now, the last year happened. One thing that happened over the last year is =
that people got really really really into trading stocks for fun. The <a hr=
ef=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/23871268.274863/aHR0cHM=
6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDEtMjUvdGhlLWdhbW=
UtbmV2ZXItc3RvcHM/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB62031dcb" itemprop=3D"StoryLink"=
 itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !im=
portant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bot=
tom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> GameStop thing</a> was probably=
 the most salient example, but broadly speaking there were a lot more peopl=
e getting into trading stocks on Robinhood, talking about stocks on Reddit=
=E2=80=99s WallStreetBets forum, learning how to trade options, and general=
ly finding their fun in the stock market. Not to mention crypto, Dogecoin, =
etc., which I think we have mentioned sufficiently at this point.</p><p sty=
le=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Another thing that happened is that people put a lot=
 of effort into making it more fun to trade stocks. Robinhood was fun, and =
many of the people who started trading stocks for the first time did it on =
Robinhood, where there was free trading and confetti and easy access to sin=
gle-stock options. Options are fun: If your goal in trading stocks is to ge=
t some excitement, trading options is a way to magnify that excitement. Wal=
lStreetBets=C2=A0is fun, and a lot of the people who started trading stocks=
 did their research and analysis and trash-talking on Reddit: Stock trading=
, in the pandemic, was not just a form of=C2=A0<em>gambling</em>, a way to =
get excitement when many other forms of excitement were unavailable; it was=
 also a form of=C2=A0<em>socializing</em>, a way to get chitchat and jokes =
and bonding when many other forms of socializing were unavailable.</p><p st=
yle=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Also stocks ended up going up a lot, despite the pa=
ndemic, which surely helped make trading more fun.</p><p style=3D"margin: 1=
6px 0;">When I first wrote about this theory, <a href=3D"https://link.mail.=
